[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p01] In computer science, big O notation is used to classify algorithms by how their run time or space requirements grow with the input.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p01] In analytic number theory, big O notation expresses bounds on the growth of an arithmetical function, as for the remainder term in the prime number theorem.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p01] In mathematical analysis, including calculus, Big O notation bounds the error when truncating a power series and expresses the quality of approximation of a real or complex valued function by a simpler function.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p01] Often, big O notation characterizes functions according to their growth rates as the variable becomes large: different functions with the same asymptotic growth rate may be represented using the same O notation.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p01] The letter O is used because the growth rate of a function is also referred to as the **order of the function**.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p01] A description of a function in terms of big O notation only provides an upper bound on the growth rate of the function.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p01] Bachmann proposed the notation in 1894 and Landau extended it in 1909.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p01] An earlier notation was proposed by Paul du Bois-Reymond in 1870.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p01] The number M {\textstyle M} ({\textstyle M}) is called the *implied constant* because it is normally not specified.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p01] When using big O {\textstyle O} ({\textstyle O}) notation, what matters is that some finite M {\displaystyle M} ({\displaystyle M}) exists, not its specific value.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p01] This simplifies the presentation of many analytic inequalities.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p01] For functions defined on positive real numbers or positive integers, a more restrictive and somewhat conflicting definition is still in common use, especially in computer science.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p01] In the 1930s, the Russian number theorist I.M.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p01] Vinogradov introduced the notation ≪ , {\displaystyle \ll ,} ({\displaystyle \ll ,}) which has been increasingly used in number theory and other branches of mathematics, as an alternative to the O {\textstyle O} ({\textstyle O}) notation.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p01] Frequently both notations are used in the same work.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p01] In computer science it is common to define big O {\textstyle O} ({\textstyle O}) as also defining a set of functions.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p01] In typical usage the O {\displaystyle O} ({\displaystyle O}) notation is applied to an infinite interval of real numbers [ a , ∞ ) {\displaystyle [a,\infty )} ({\displaystyle [a,\infty )}) and captures the behavior of the function for very large x {\displaystyle x} ({\displaystyle x}).
