[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p01] An algorithm can require time that is both superpolynomial and subexponential; examples of this include the fastest known algorithms for integer factorization and the function n log ⁡ n {\displaystyle n^{\log n}} ({\displaystyle n^{\log n}}).
