[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p02] The symbol O was first introduced by the number theorist Paul Bachmann in 1894, in the second volume of his book *Analytische Zahlentheorie* ("analytic number theory").
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p02] The number theorist Edmund Landau adopted it, and was thus inspired to introduce in 1909 the notation o; hence both are now called Landau symbols.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p02] These notations were used in applied mathematics during the 1950s for asymptotic analysis.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p02] The symbol Ω {\displaystyle \Omega } ({\displaystyle \Omega }) (in the sense "is not little *o* of") was introduced in 1914 by Hardy and Littlewood.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p02] This Ω {\displaystyle \Omega } ({\displaystyle \Omega }) notation has been commonly used in number theory since the 1950s.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p02] In his nearly 400 remaining papers and books he consistently used the Landau symbols O and o.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p02] The symbol ∼ {\displaystyle \sim } ({\displaystyle \sim }), although it had been used before with different meanings, was given its modern definition by Landau in 1909 and by Hardy in 1910.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p02] The notation is still used in analytic number theory.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p02] This notation became standard in analytic number theory.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p02] In mathematics, an expression such as x → ∞ {\displaystyle x\to \infty } ({\displaystyle x\to \infty }) indicates the presence of a limit.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p02] Notation such as f ( x ) = O ( g ( x ) ) ( x → ∞ ) {\displaystyle f(x)=O(g(x))\;\;(x\to \infty )} ({\displaystyle f(x)=O(g(x))\;\;(x\to \infty )}) can be considered an abuse of notation.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p02] Some consider f ( x ) = O ( g ( x ) ) {\displaystyle f(x)=O(g(x))} ({\displaystyle f(x)=O(g(x))}) to also be an abuse of notation, since the use of the equals sign could be misleading as it suggests a symmetry that this statement does not have.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p02] The Vinogradov notations ≪ {\displaystyle \ll } ({\displaystyle \ll }) and ≫ {\displaystyle \gg } ({\displaystyle \gg }), which are widely used in number theory do not suffer from this defect, as they more clearly indicate that big-O indicates an *inequality* rather than an *equality*.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p02] They also enjoy a symmetry that big-O notation lacks: f ( x ) ≪ g ( x ) {\displaystyle f(x)\ll g(x)} ({\displaystyle f(x)\ll g(x)}) means the same as g ( x ) ≫ f ( x ) {\displaystyle g(x)\gg f(x)} ({\displaystyle g(x)\gg f(x)}).
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p02] In combinatorics and computer science, these notations are rarely seen.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p02] Big O is typeset as an italicized uppercase "O", as in the following example: O ( n 2 ) {\displaystyle O(n^{2})} ({\displaystyle O(n^{2})}).
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p02] In TeX, it is produced by simply typing 'O' inside math mode.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p02] Unlike Greek-named Bachmann–Landau notations, it needs no special symbol.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p02] However, some authors use the calligraphic variant O {\displaystyle {\mathcal {O}}} ({\displaystyle {\mathcal {O}}}) instead.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p02] The big-O originally stands for "order of" ("Ordnung", Bachmann 1894), and is thus a Latin letter.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p02] Neither Bachmann nor Landau ever call it "Omicron".
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation-p02] The symbol was much later on (1976) viewed by Knuth as a capital omicron, probably in reference to his definition of the symbol Omega.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] Associated with big O notation are several related notations, using the symbols o , $\sim$ , $\Omega$ , $\ll$ , $\gg$ , $\asymp$ , $\omega$ , and $\Theta$ to describe other kinds of bounds on growth rates.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] In most applications, one chooses the function $g(x)$ appearing within the argument of ${\textstyle O{\bigl (}\cdot {\bigr )}}$ to be as simple a form as possible, omitting constant factors and lower order terms.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] The number ${\textstyle M}$ is called the *implied constant* because it is normally not specified.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] When using big ${\textstyle O}$ notation, what matters is that some finite M exists, not its specific value.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] Vinogradov introduced the notation $\ll ,$ which has been increasingly used in number theory and other branches of mathematics, as an alternative to the ${\textstyle O}$ notation.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] In computer science it is common to define big ${\textstyle O}$ as also defining a set of functions.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] In typical usage the O notation is applied to an infinite interval of real numbers $[a,\infty )$ and captures the behavior of the function for very large x .
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] For example, let $f(x)=6x^{4}-2x^{3}+5$ , and suppose we wish to simplify this function, using O notation, to describe its growth rate for large x .
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] Of these three terms, the one with the highest growth rate is the one with the largest exponent as a function of x , namely $6x^{4}$ .
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] Now one may apply the second rule: $6x^{4}$ is a product of 6 and $x^{4}$ in which the first factor does not depend on x .
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] Omitting this factor results in the simplified form $x^{4}$ .
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] Thus, we say that $f(x)$ is a "big O" of $x^{4}$ .
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] Mathematically, we can write $f(x)=O(x^{4})$ for all $x\geq 1$ .
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] One may confirm this calculation using the formal definition: let $f(x)=6x^{4}-2x^{3}+5$ and $g(x)=x^{4}$ .
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] Applying the formal definition from above, the statement that $f(x)=O(x^{4})$ is equivalent to its expansion, $|f(x)|\leq Mx^{4}$ for some suitable choice of a positive real number M and for all $x\geq 1$ .
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] On the other hand, the statement $f(x)=O(x^{3})$ is false, because the term $6x^{4}$ causes $f(x)/x^{3}$ to be unbounded.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] When a function $T(n)$ describes the number of steps required in an algorithm with input n , an expression such as $T(n)=O(n^{2})$ with the implied domain being the set of positive integers, may be interpreted as saying that the algorithm has *at most the order of $n^{2}$* time complexity.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] In general, any bounded function is $O(1)$ .
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] Sometimes in a multivariate expression, one variable is more important than others, and one may express that the implied constant M depends on one or more of the variables using subscripts to the big O symbol or the $\ll$ symbol.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] This means that for each real number b , there is a constant $M_{b}$ , *which depends on b*, so that for all $0\leq x\leq 1$ , $|(1+x)^{b}-1|\leq M_{b}\cdot x.$ This particular statement follows from the general binomial theorem.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] Another example, common in the theory of Taylor series, is $e^{x}=1+x+O_{r}(x^{2})\quad {\text{ for all }}|x|\leq r,r{\text{ being any real number.}}$ Here the implied constant depends on the size of the domain.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] If the function f of a positive integer n can be written as a finite sum of other functions, then the fastest growing one determines the order of $f(n)$ .
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] For any positive $a,b,$ $(\log n)^{a}=O_{a,b}(n^{b}),$ no matter how large a is and how small b is.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] Here, the implied constant depends on both a and b .
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] For any positive $a,b,$ $n^{a}=O_{a,b}(e^{bn}),$ no matter how large a is and how small b is.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] A function that grows faster than $n^{c}$ for any c is called *superpolynomial*.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] One that grows more slowly than any exponential function of the form $c^{n}$ with $c>1$ is called *subexponential*.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] An algorithm can require time that is both superpolynomial and subexponential; examples of this include the fastest known algorithms for integer factorization and the function $n^{\log n}$ .
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] We may ignore any powers of n inside of the logarithms.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] For any positive c , the notation $O(\log n)$ means exactly the same thing as $O(\log(n^{c}))$ , since $\log(n^{c})=c\log n$ .
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] For example, $2^{n}$ and $3^{n}$ are not of the same order.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] In more complicated usage, $O(\cdot )$ can appear in different places in an equation, even several times on each side.
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] For example, the third equation above means: "For any function satisfying $f(n)=O(1)$ , there is some function $g(n)=O(e^{n})$ such that $n^{f(n)}=g(n)$ ".
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] The implied constant in the statement " $g(n)=O(e^{n})$ " may depend on the implied constant in the expression " $f(n)=O(1)$ ".
[src:algorithms/big-o-notation] When $f,g$ are both positive functions, Vinogradov introduced the notation $f(x)\gg g(x)$ , which means the same as $g(x)=O(f(x))$ .
